HTML Attributes - Definition and Usage

01-accept 
When you upload a file, only the files of the type configured in the accept attribute: image files or text-only files will be shown in the window. 
It can only be used <input type="file">. Do not use this attribute as a validation tool because the files are validated on the server.

Applies to element: input

Example:
Specify that the server accepts only image files in the file upload:
<form action="/action_page.php">
  <input type="file" name="pic" accept="image/*">
  <input type="submit">
</form>

02-accept-charset
Sets the charset character to use in the form submission. 
When not set a value the default is unknown by taking the value of the document that contains the form element

Applies to element: form

Example:
<form action="/action_page.php" accept-charset="ISO-8859-1">
  First name: <input type="text" name="fname"><br>
  Last name: <input type="text" name="lname"><br>
  <input type="submit" value="Submit">
</form>

03-accesskey
Sets a shortcut key to activate/focus an element.
The accesskey attribute value must be a single character (a letter or a digit).

Applies to element: All HTML elements

Note:
Most browsers will use the access keys only with the Alt key pressed, to avoid conflicts with the browser's own shortcut patterns.
It is not advisable to use access keys because the value of the access key may not be present on some keyboards (other languages)

Syntax
<element accesskey="
character">

Example:
<a href="https://www.w3schools.com/html/" accesskey="h">HTML</a><br>
<a href="https://www.w3schools.com/css/" accesskey="c">CSS</a>

04-action
This attribute specifies where to send the form-data when a form is submitted.

Applies to element: form 

Example:
<form action="/action_page.php" method="get">
  First name: <input type="text" name="fname"><br>
  Last name: <input type="text" name="lname"><br>
  <input type="submit" value="Submit">
</form>

05-alt
Use the alt attribute to define text of what the image is about, if it is not displayed for some reason, 
whether it is a slow connection, an error in the src attribute, or if the user uses a screen reader, 

Note: The alt attribute is required for the <img>element.
      For <input>, the alt attribute can only be used with <input type="image">.

Tip: To create a tooltip for an image, use the title attribute!

Applies to element:
area, img, input

Example:
1-
<form action="/action_page.php">
  First name: <input type="text" name="fname"><br>
  <input type="image" src="submit.gif" alt="Submit" width="48" height="48">
</form>

2-
<img src="smiley.gif" alt="Smiley face">

3-
<form action="/action_page.php">
  First name: <input type="text" name="fname"><br>
  <input type="image" src="submit.gif" alt="Submit" width="48" height="48">
</form>

06-async
Specifies that the script will be executed asynchronously as soon as it is available.
If async is present: The script will run while the page continues analysis (asynchronously).
If async is not present and deferral is present: The script runs when the page finishes parsing.
If neither async nor postponement is present: The script is fetched and executed immediately, before the browser continues analyzing the page
Note: The async attribute is for external scripts only and will only be used if the src attribute is present.

Applies to element: script

Example:
A script that will be run asynchronously as soon as it is available:
<script src="demo_async.js" async></script>

